THE Eastern Cape government is on a mission to end all forms of violence against women and children.On Monday, Eastern Cape social development MEC Nancy Sihlwayi was joined by provincial police commissioner Major-General Liziwe Ntshinga and victims of gender-based violence at Radisson Blue Hotel in Port Elizabeth. The event was aimed at hearing the experiences of victims and their families.Reeva Steenkamp&rsquo;s family was also at the event. Steenkamp was murdered by her sprint runner Oscar Pistorius, her boyfriend. MEC Sihlwayi said: &ldquo;The lessons learnt will help the government create strategies for the 16 Days of Activism for No Violence Against Women and Children campaign. &ldquo;Our aim is to create a platform for victims to raise awareness about the factors that influence abuse.&rdquo;It is estimated that one in five women in South Africa are victims of gender-based violence.&ldquo;This chilling statistic should be enough to indicate that there is a need to stand up and fight against gender-based violence.&rdquo;The anti-abuse campaign will be observed from Friday until 10 December.